            <h3>Conditional statements</h3>
            <p>Conditional statements in Java allow you to execute different blocks of code based on whether certain conditions are met. Java provides several conditional statements, including if, else, else if, and switch. Here's an overview of how these conditional statements work:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <h5>if Statement</h5><p>An "if" statement is like making a decision based on a condition. If a specific condition is true, you do something; if it's not true, you skip that action.
                        <br>Example: If it's raining outside, you take an umbrella</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h5>if-else Statement:</h5><p>An "if-else" statement is like having two options based on a condition. If a condition is true, you do one thing; if it's false, you do something else.
                        <br>Example: If you have money in your pocket, you buy ice cream; otherwise, you go home.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h5>If- else if - else Statement: </h5><p> An "if-else if-else" statement is like having many choices but making only one. It checks multiple conditions in order and picks the first true one.
                        <br>Example: In a restaurant, if you're very hungry, you order a big meal; if you're a little hungry, you order a snack; otherwise, you order dessert.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h5>switch Statement: </h5><p>A "switch" statement is like a menu with many choices. You pick one based on a value, and it takes you to that choice's action.
                       <br> Example: Imagine a vending machine. When you press a button (like "Coke" or "Chips"), it gives you that item based on your choice.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
